{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c253696f-b3cb-4ee4-b2d3-197cbcc1bafa","content":"Your project uses **MSTest 3.8** with **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (MTP). Run with blame-hang to detect the hanging test:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThis will:\n1. Monitor each test for a 5-minute timeout\n2. Collect a hang dump if any test exceeds the limit\n3. Report which test was hanging\n\nThe dump files will be written to `TestResults/` in your project directory. You can also add `--blame-hang-dump-type full` for a complete memory dump if you need deeper analysis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"96202cb3-287d-478d-b2fa-39536938f7be","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project uses MSTest 3.8.0 on .NET 10 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) as the runner (configured via global.json). For MTP, the blame-hang option is passed differently than VSTest.\n\nFor MTP, the hang dump option is `--blame-hang` with `--blame-hang-timeout <duration>`. Let me provide the right command.\n\nActually, with MTP runner, the command-line arguments are different. Let me think about this...\n\nFor MSTest with MTP runner, you use `--blame-hang` and `--blame-hang-timeout` directly as CLI arguments to `dotnet test`. The timeout format is like `5m` or `300s` or `00:05:00`.\n\n\nBoth VSTest and MTP platforms support these same arguments when invoked through `dotnet test`, so the command passes `--blame-hang` and `--blame-hang-timeout` with a duration like `5m` directly to capture hang dumps.","outputTokens":411,"requestId":"BD01:4FC4C:215C949:25E7456:6A07DFAF"},"id":"7f9c4d6d-90ec-4544-a1f7-85b7bd1d8432","timestamp":"2026-05-16T03:08:46.184Z","parentId":"9962b211-8c47-4fdb-84ea-c896f99932db"}
